# WebGL / Shader Rules

## Architecture

- Shader components live in `web/components/ui/`
- Always `"use client"` — WebGL needs browser APIs
- Load via `next/dynamic` with `ssr: false` from parent
- Reference: `shader-animation.tsx` (intro), `animated-shader-background.tsx` (hero)

## Performance

- Dispose Three.js resources on unmount (geometry, material, renderer)
- Use `requestAnimationFrame` loop; cancel in cleanup
- Avoid creating new objects inside the render loop
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` when adding motion-heavy effects

## Intro overlay

- `ShaderAnimation` accepts `onIntroEnd`, `forceSkipIntro`
- Dev mode skips intro (`NODE_ENV === "development"`)
- Fallback timeout (~6s) in `landing-page.tsx` if intro stalls

## Adding new effects

1. Copy pattern from existing shader component
2. Export typed props interface
3. Parent wraps with `dynamic(..., { ssr: false, loading: () => ... })`
4. Test build — shaders must not break static export
